{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox person | name = Neema Barnette | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | birthname = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|12|14}} | birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States | death_date = | death_place = | othername = | occupation = Director, producer | yearsactive = 1982–present | spouse = Reed R. McCants (1 child) | domesticpartner = | website = }}
'''Neema Barnette''' is an American film director,<ref name="latimes2003"/><ref name="nytimes2003"/> and the first African-American woman sitcom director.<ref name="tribune1993"/> Barnette was the first African-American woman to get a three-picture deal with Sony.{{citation needed|date=November 2009}}
In 1990, she founded Harlem Girl Productions Corporation. Since 1997, Barnette has also worked for the Harlem Lite Productions. She has directed multiple seasons and episodes of a variety of television sitcoms including ''[[A Different World (TV series)|A Different World]]'', ''[[The Cosby Show]]'', ''[[Gilmore Girls]]'', and ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''.
Barnette has directed stage, episodic television, made for TV movies and feature films. ''[[Sky Captain (1985 film)|Sky Captain]]'' was her first short film which she directed as part of the American Film Institute's (AFI) Directing Workshop for Women in 1985.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Women Who Run the Show: How a Brilliant and Creative New Generation of Women Stormed Hollywood|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=II4aKRa7CUMC|publisher = Macmillan|date = 2002-08-24|isbn = 9780312301828|first = Mollie|last = Gregory}}</ref> Her 2003 film ''[[Civil Brand]]'' is a low-budget feature on women in prison who stage an uprising to protest their treatment.<ref name="nytimes2003" /> Her 1997 film, ''[[Spirit Lost]],'' is a psychological thriller with a love triangle that includes a ghost.<ref name="latimes2003" /><ref name="recorder1995" />
Her most recent feature film is ''[[Woman Thou Art Loosed: On The 7th Day]]'' (2012), her 11th movie and third for theatrical release.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Woman Thou Art Loosed: On the 7th Day: Film Review|url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/woman-thou-art-loosed-7th-day-312189|website = The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate = 2015-12-13}}</ref> The film is a thriller and family drama following the story of a marriage on the rocks,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Woman-Thou-Art-Loosed-On-the-7th-Day - Trailer - Cast - Showtimes - NYTimes.com|url = https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/466515/Woman-Thou-Art-Loosed-On-the-7th-Day/overview|website = www.nytimes.com|accessdate = 2015-12-13}}</ref> which received an NAACP Image Award Nomination for Best Independent Feature in 2012.<ref name="About BHMD">{{Cite web|title = About BHMD|url = http://www.blackhistoryminidocs.com/about.html|website = www.blackhistoryminidocs.com|accessdate = 2015-12-13|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222102211/http://www.blackhistoryminidocs.com/about.html|archivedate = December 22, 2015|df = mdy-all}}</ref> Barnette directed two episodes of ''Being Mary Jane'': "Hot Seat" and "Don't Call It A Comeback" (2015 - Season 3).<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0056006/|title = Barnette|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = Neema|first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Being Mary Jane Season 3|url = http://seasonepisode.me/being-mary-jane/season-3-being-mary-jane/|website = Season Episode.me|accessdate = 2015-12-13|language = en-US}}</ref> Barnette is the Executive Producer of Black History Mini Docs, 90 second videos featuring the stories of African-American heroes and she-roes, as well as daily tributes which are posted on Facebook, Twitter & Pinterest.<ref name="About BHMD"/>
She has won numerous awards, honors, and nominations, among them an Emmy Award for her afterschool special ''To Be a Man'',<ref name="npr2009" /> two [[NAACP Image Awards]], and a [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance Film Festival Award]].{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}
