'''Nise-e''' (似絵), or "likeness pictures," were a style of [[portrait painting|portraiture]] popular in the [[Court (royal)|court]] circles of Japan's [[Kamakura period]].<ref name="auto">{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/nise-e|title=nise-e {{!}} Japanese art|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-05-28|language=en}}</ref> Prior to the 12th century [[Japanese art]] was purely religious in character, but nise-e introduced the realistic depiction of [[Laity|lay]] figures such as [[Courtier|courtiers]] and [[samurai]].<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steiner|first=Evgeny|date=2013|title=Zen Portraits Chinzō: Why do They Look as They do?|url=https://terebess.hu/zen/szoto/Chinzo.docx|journal=Terebess Asia Online|volume=|pages=|via=Google Scholar}}</ref> The popularity of nise-e even helped to end the [[taboo]] against artistic depictions of the emperor, with one of earliest nise-e to depict a living [[Emperor of Japan|emperor]] being a portrait of [[Emperor Hanazono]] by [https://commons.m.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Emperor_Hanazono_large.jpg Gōshin].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hirayama|first=Mikiko|title=The Emperor's New Clothes: Japanese Visuality and Imperial Portrait Photography|journal=History of Photography|volume=33|issue=2|pages=165–184|doi=10.1080/03087290902768099|year=2011}}</ref> The aim of a nise-e portrait was to capture a man's character with a few simple lines; and the work served as a veneration of his accomplishments.<ref name="auto"/> 

[[Fujiwara Takanobu]] is generally considered to have originated the nise-e style and technique.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Takanobu|url=http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/benezit/B00179192|journal=Benezit Dictionary of Artists|volume=|pages=|via=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> He innovated the use of jutting, angular outlines and dense swaths of color which came to characterize nise-e portraiture as a whole.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Fujiwara-Takanobu|title=Fujiwara Takanobu {{!}} Japanese painter|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-05-28|language=en}}</ref> Takanobu's influence is seen in the works of his son [[Fujiwara Nobuzane]], and descendants Tametsugu, Korenobu, Tamenobu, and Gōshin, who continued to develop the nise-e school alongside others such as Shinkai and Tametaga.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Fujiwara-Nobuzane|title=Fujiwara Nobuzane {{!}} Japanese painter|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-05-28|language=en}}</ref><ref name="auto"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Nobuzane|url=http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/benezit/B00131087|journal=Benezit Dictionary of Artists|volume=|pages=|via=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> Nise-e portraiture also greatly influenced the 18th century portrait style ''nigao-e'' (likeness head), pioneered by [[Katsukawa Shunshō]]  in response to a desire for [[Kabuki|actor]] portraits with realistic and expressive facial features.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Shunsho|url=http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/benezit/B00168949|journal=Benezit Dictionary of Artists|volume=|pages=|via=Oxford Art Online}}</ref>

